'''Rudolph Grey''' is a [[musician]] and [[writer]].

As an [[electric guitar]]ist, Grey has recorded and performed under his own name, as well as leading various [[ad hoc]] ensembles called [[The Blue Humans]]<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:fzfuxqy5ld0e~T1 The Blue Humans bio in Allmusic.com]</ref>. His music draws on [[no wave]] and [[free jazz]].

Grey is also a motion picture historian and has written ''Nightmare of Ecstasy'' (1992), a biography of [[Edward D. Wood, Jr.|Ed Wood]], the director of notoriously awful films. [[Tim Burton]] drew heavily on ''Nightmare'' for his film ''[[Ed Wood (film)|Ed Wood]]''.

In 2001, Grey rediscovered a copy of Ed Wood's final feature-length film, ''[[Necromania]]'', which had been presumed to be lost.<ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/10/25/041025ta_talk_paumgarten Weird Love]</ref>

